00:01.260 --> 00:11.720
Just a brief statement on how you became a professional writer, the background
that led you to it Well it's, you know, everybody's story is a long story It's

00:11.720 --> 00:22.580
much easier for other people to summarize you than it is for you to summarize
yourself I conceived in college the ambition to be a professional writer of

00:22.580 --> 00:33.220
fiction It was a number of years before I stumbled into writing fantasy and that
was a crucial thing for me because my writing got a great deal better when I

00:33.220 --> 00:44.580
started to write fantasy but that had been about 8 years I had been writing as
hard as I knew how for 8 years before I started on fantasy and from the time I

00:44.580 --> 00:57.800
started writing fantasy until I finally achieved a publication of some kind was
another 5 years so I had a a 13-year apprenticeship in a sense and then it's

00:57.800 --> 01:08.220
been only since then that I've been able to support myself as a writer. Did you
grow up reading science fiction? Well, actually no. And not for any other reason

01:08.220 --> 01:16.560
than in terms of what I call a historical accident. I was living in India
because my parents were medical missionaries to India and we simply got a very

01:16.560 --> 01:26.420
erratic supply of books. There was no one particular kind of thing that we got
except mystery novels. Missionaries love to read mystery novels. I don't know

01:26.420 --> 01:37.040
quite why that is. But other than that, it was a random sampling of everything.
I read Leon Urus and the Hardy Boys at the same time, and I read Bamba the

01:37.040 --> 01:47.860
Jungle Boy, and I read James Michener, and a whole range of things, whatever I
could get my hands on. Now, I loved every science fiction novel that I got my

01:47.860 --> 01:59.540
hands on, of which I can remember every one. There were three. I read three by
the time I was a high school graduate. One was Alfred Bester's The Star Is My

01:59.540 --> 02:10.880
Destination. One was A.J. Boudry's Rogue Moon. And one was Theodore Sturgeon's
More Than Human. Now, it's just an accident that I happened to get to read three

02:10.880 --> 02:21.320
classics in the only three science fiction books I read. They made a great
impression on me, but that was all there was. Now, I came to the United States

02:21.320 --> 02:30.640
at the end of my high school days to start college, and I wanted to read more
science fiction, but I didn't know any people who read it. So I didn't know any

02:30.640 --> 02:39.020
place to get information about what was worth reading. And what I would do is
wander into a drugstore and pick up a science fiction book. And you can get some

02:39.020 --> 02:47.020
remarkably bad books doing that. And the things that I picked up in the first
couple of years in drugstores were so terrible that I stopped reading science

02:47.020 --> 02:57.740
fiction. And in fact, I didn't start reading science fiction again until I was
finally in a position where I knew people who could make recommendations to

02:57.740 --> 03:00.560
separate out the real garbage from the good stuff.

