05:15.800 --> 05:28.840
this was unfair question I'm sure it's too general to be really fair one but was
there a particular impetus behind that novel? Well, that is pretty gentle. I

05:28.840 --> 05:37.120
don't know what kind of impetus you're talking about. When you started to write,
was there something in your mind that said, I want to write a novel of this type

05:37.120 --> 05:48.240
about Thomas Covenant, who's a leper and so forth? Well, the key thing for me
about The Chronicles of Thomas Covenant was that my inspiration for it came from

05:48.240 --> 06:00.360
the end. The first idea that occurred for me for that book was for the climax of
The Power That Preserves. Now, when I got a story going, I had an entire story

06:00.360 --> 06:09.420
ready to tell. And from that point of view, the impetus that got me going on
Lord Foul's Bane was the climax of The Power That Preserves. And that has been my

06:09.420 --> 06:17.680
pattern in all the Covenant books is that I have worked them all backwards. I
mean, I don't write them backwards, but I plan them and arrange them backwards.

06:17.680 --> 06:27.800
The thing that inspires me to write the story comes at the end. So with the
second Chronicles, it was the climax of White Gold Wielder that convinced me

06:27.800 --> 06:35.820
that I wanted to write a second Chronicles. And essentially, my method is that I
have this climactic

06:35.820 --> 06:44.840
scene in mind, and I have to answer the simple questions like, who are these
guys and how did they get into this mess? And I plan backwards on that basis.

06:44.980 --> 06:52.660
Well, in order for that to happen, these things must have happened first. And if
those things must have happened first, then these kinds of people must have been

06:52.660 --> 07:03.180
doing those kinds of things. And I arrange everything backwards until I get to a
point where I can start writing, which means that the one thing that's

07:03.180 --> 07:10.360
absolutely clear to me the whole time when I'm working on these things, I know
where I'm going. I know exactly what the purpose of all these events is. It's

07:10.360 --> 07:21.700
going to produce that result, which you as a reader will finally come to at the
end of 1,500 pages or whatever. And in the case of the first Chronicles, it was

07:21.700 --> 07:33.360
that climactic scene where Thomas Covenant, who has been rejecting the
importance of his fantasy experience, comes face to face with Lord Foul. And

07:33.360 --> 07:50.220
the fact that he disbelieves in some way in the reality of the fantasy gives him
the emotional power to not be crushed by Lord Foul. He knows he doesn't need

07:50.220 --> 08:01.720
to be overwhelmed by evil because he denies its external reality. I mean, he
knows there's evil in him, but he doesn't have to be overwhelmed by this

08:01.720 --> 08:13.780
externalization of evil. And that makes it possible for him to win. Well, I knew
that was where I was going the entire time I worked on the first trilogy. Okay.

